private life, I have &quot;true mode on&quot;, a small friends list but those are great and know my true nature which is by far more important to me than anything else. I think we both agree that social science is important in RL and EQ. My point of view is that this is crappy. I'd like to have your main feeling about it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Well, I have to confess, when I discovered that this is how people work, I was angry about it, and tried to rebel against it.  It bothered me enormously that people could not just accept me as I was, and see my value.<br>
<br>
However, you might as well try to rebel against gravity, as I discovered as I learned more.  No, social science is not nearly as precise or deterministic as say physics, but it does act like both current and friction, dragging most but not all in its direction.<br>
<br>
Simple fact remains.  I cut my hair, shaved, put on this business suit, and all of sudden they pay me a LOT more money, and I have a nice house in downtown San Jose.  When I was &quot;myself&quot; and dressed like a hippy, well, I didn't make a whole lot of money. <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Raz, I was just pointing out that you later in your argument said that in certain situation some classes have an easier time getting into the most <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>popular</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> group type. Both statements cannot be true since the primary grouping form in the game is though the &quot;classic group&quot;. So &quot;Grouping&quot; <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>as defined by the majority of groups in the game</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> has to include the &quot;Classic Group&quot;.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Not sure how to respond to this, since this seems to involve a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;blind spot&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of yours.  I will do my best.<br>
<br>
Objectively, as defined by game mechanics, a group consists of a leader and up to five other players whom the leader has invited and whom have agreed to join the group.<br>
<br>
A group style is set of roles and tactics for the members of a speficic group.  All group styles are social constructs.  That is, the roles and tactics are creations based on choice by the potential group participants.<br>
<br>
There are some constraints on successful experience groups, which I have described before.  A successful group must include adequate damage dealing, and adequate damage mitigation.  These minimal requirements comprise the only objective roles in the group.<br>
<br>
All specific group styles and the roles they contain are created solutions to the essential problem of killing things and not getting killed.  They are chosen by the participants.  This thread has already named several different group styles.  These include <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Classic, Area of Effect, Pet Centered,</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Fear Kiting</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Each style has it own set of roles, and different classes differ in the ability to fulfil the available roles in that group.  For example, pure melees are generally sub-par in pet centered groups as they tend to take aggro from the pets, defeating the main advantages of that style.  Likewise, melees are generally sub-par in area of effect groups.  From this should I conclude that melees are sub-par, and in need of dramatic improvements?<br>
<br>
Of course not.  I would never pretend that area of effect groups are the end-all and be-all of groups, and the central basis for judging the relative merit of the various classes.<br>
<br>
However, for some reason you claim it is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;objective&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> that the classic group style is the standard against which all classes should be judged <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (and so Magicians found wanting)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  How can this possibly be?  The only criteria you suggest is:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> ...as defined by the majority...the most popular...<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Can you <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>really</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> mean this?  Does popularity of an idea imply its objective truth?<br>
<br>
There is no doubt that the classic group style is quite adequate and performs well under a fairly broad range of circumstances.  But neither its adequacy nor its popularity elevate it to some objective icon of truth.  Popularity is at best suggestive, it is never conclusive by itself.<br>
<br>
Have you some criteria in mind?  Although you have not suggested anything other than popularity, here are some criteria we might judge groups by:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Experience gained per hour:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> This is a common argument made in favor of the classic group style, and for certain camps it has few peers.  However, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Area of Effect Groups</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> can easily outperform it, as can the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Six Mage Group</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Applicability:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Another advantage of classic group is that it works in many places.  However, due to the popularity of the group style the best camps for this style are well known and often occupied.  The vast majority of classic groups therefore instead make due with merely adequate camps, which do not live up to its potential.  While it is true that other group styles, such as <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Area of Effect</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> or <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Fear Kiting</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> may have more strict requirements for spawns, other styles, such as <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Pet centered</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, prosper where other groups do not.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Robustness:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> How does the group cope with changes in composition.  The classic group, especially in optimal camp for that style, are brittle, and must break up or surrender the camp if a key member leaves.  If either the main tank, or the healer, or the crowd control leave, the good times come to an end.  In contrast, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Fear Kiting Groups</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> has only two key roles, and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Pet Centered Groups</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> are very flexible for replacing members. By this critera, the classic group is inferior.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Recruitment:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> How easy is it to recruit members for the group.  By this measure, the classic group both benefits and is limited by its own popularity.  On the one hand, because the form is popular, many players have chosen character classes that are appropriate for that style, but on the other hand there is intense competition for recruiting key classes for the group.  There are many camps where if you cannot recruit an enchanter or bard, then there is no group.  Time spent recruiting the group is time not playing, and time waiting to be recruited is also time not played.  In contrast, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Pet Centered Groups</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> being more flexible in the allowed classes, many of which do not face heavy competions, are easier to recruit.<br>
<br>
There are perhaps other criteria one could propose for measuring group style effectiveness, but even in this short list, the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Classic Group</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> does not necessarily stand out head and shoulders above other groups.<br>
<br>
In any case, one must <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>chose</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> a set of criteria and weigh their relative values.<br>
<br>
Nothing <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>objective</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> about that <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>choice</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->.<br>
<br>
Popular != Objective Best<br>
<br>
If you mistake the shared opinions and choices of a large number of people for objective truth, then you are destined to driven blindly about like some herd animal.  I prefer to examine my assumptions, and the assumptions of those around me, to see more clearly what truth might be contained within.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Razamatazz Pizzazz</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
ArchAbuser of Science<br>
