<br>
But the fact that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> may be sub-par in this camp, and even other camps like it, should not be generalized to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in groups in general.  Yet, in fact, this is exactly what people do.  Possibly because even if they do not have such a camp, they are hoping that they can get a group that can take that camp.  That does not mean either that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> are sub-par for the camp they have, or that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in general are sub-par.  It does suggest that people have a tendency to over generalize.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> argue against points that are just so obvious<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I maintain that this is not nearly so obvious as you think.  That obvious, more often than not, means unexamined, unexplained, or assumed.<br>
<br>
Class value is situational, and what I am saying is that people have over-generalized.  That is, they have taken some perfectly valid observations about a perfectly valid group style that performs very well for some camps, and adequately well for many others, and made the mistake of concluding that the relative value of classes in that group style apply in general.  Worse, by seeking only variations of those camps which are appropriate for that style, it reinforces the impression.  Repeated often enough, the uncritical accept this as being objectively true.  Certainly it is easier that way, and implies that analysis is worthless and contradictory evidence can be dismissed as anomolies at best.<br>
<br>
Popularity of a particular view is not sufficient to demonstrate its truth or objective value.  A whole lot of people can be very, very wrong.<br>
<br>
I persist in the folly of trying to rebut this because it illustrates some very important points generally.  The central point here is that things which are obvious are often exactly what should be most critically examined.  An assumption that you do not even know you are making can be a crippling blind spot.<br>
<br>
I think you would be hard pressed to claim that I do not have adequate intelligence.  I demonstrate competence with language, arguments, and math, and analyze, create and refute complex logical arguments.<br>
<br>
Why not, even just as a thought experiment, consider the possibility that I might be correct, and that there is more here than meets the eye.  That that which is obvious is not obvious, but perhaps even false.  Just as an intellectual game, if you will.  At the very least, you will find the ability to see things as others see them an invaluable skill in motivating and convincing other people.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Raz</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=wezloc>WEZLOC</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Arch Mage</span><br>  Posts: 413<br> <font color=#333333>(3/28/02 7:55:44 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=163.topic&index=56>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_exclamation_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Difficulty with grouping in 50+ or just cause I am a mag</span><hr size=1> &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;I think you would be hard pressed to claim that I do not have adequate intelligence. I demonstrate competence with language, arguments, and math, and analyze, create and refute complex logical arguments.<br>
<br>
I see the above statement as nothing more then ego massaging. It basically implies that because you are educated and write well that you are somehow superior in your thinking to those that have not attended college or have experienced higher education.  Note that the FBI reports show that those that are most educated (college grads or higher) fall victim to cults and groups of that kind more often then people that have not been apart of &quot;higher learning&quot; so to speak.<br>
<br>
Alot of people in this thread do not agree with you and I happen to be one of them. Everyone is entitled to there own opinion and rightly so you are entitled to yours. To continue to analzye what everyone is saying and to put out the perception that because you have attended college and have a way with words that you somehow have the upper hand on thinking, and because they dont agree with you they are somehow not clearly looking at all the evidence is simply wrong and a bit snobbish.<br>
<br>
I have been playing EQ for almost 3 years now. I have a 58 bard, 58 druid, 56 magician and a 52 monk as well as some other classes lower then 50.  You have said more then once that you do not have any alt nor do you wish to play any. Well IMHO this makes your point of view short sided. If you played another class (enchanter/bard/cleric) then you would see that alot of magicians problems have nothing to do with perception and alot to do with reality.  A magicians will not get a group in a indoor group or out door group as quickly as a enchanter/cleric/bard/warrior/rogue/monk. People learn at a very low lvl that enchanters have breeze, clerics have rez and monks make the best pullers.  Rogues and monks even at the low lvls now due to twinking are seen as premier damage dealers. If a enchanter or mage is shouting for group even if the group doesnt really need crowd control they will take the enchanter.  Being able to slow, clarity, mezz, haste, and provide nuking is enough to win out over merely  damage dealing in most cases. It is the same at higher lvls when it comes to damage. A rogue will most always get picked over a magicians. It is because those classes are better at what they do and post 50 everything is about specialization and magicians are just not specialized.  <br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;Why not, even just as a thought experiment, consider the possibility that I might be correct, and that there is more here than meets the eye. That that which is obvious is not obvious, but perhaps even false. Just as an intellectual game, if you will. At the very least, you will find the ability to see things as others see them an invaluable skill in motivating and convincing other people.<br>
<br>
I have a proposal for you. Why not as a experiment you try playing a enchanter/rogue/cleric for two weeks. Get them to about lvl 30 and then tell me if everyone that is against what you are saying is wrong? It is easy to say it is perception when you have not played another class. I think because you have not you lack perception and dept on this argument because by playing only one class you have blinders on.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uzebanar01.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Zebanar01</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Master Summoner</span><br>  Posts: 166<br> <font color=#333333>(3/28/02 9:25:18 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=163.topic&index=57>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_exclamation_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  The only way..</span><hr size=1> After review of this...I have to say that we cannot determine whether it is primarily a social or a class balance issue. We don't have the information we need to find that out. Nor will we. Ever.<br>
<br>
We would need a comprehensive database of damage dealt per level, for every class. A list of all possible ways of controlling mobs. A list of all other useful abilities a class has to offer. Their dependancies on others, etc. It comes out to be an insane amount of variables. <br>
<br>
If we were to take the results of that study(which is somehow unbias), and then come churn out a ranking system for each class, then we could determine the answer to our question. <br>
<br>
In order to answer this we would have to prove that the magician is, in all circumstances less viable than any other class. Its an unprovable point. Balanz will win by default because we KNOW that social issues do indeed play a factor. <br>
<br>
