There are ofcourse the classes more wanted then mages, like clerics and enchanters. But aside from the obviously more group valuable classes so are mages in a decent position. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=kryskin>Kryskin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 40<br> <font color=#333333>(3/28/02 11:46:20 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=163.topic&index=59>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_exclamation_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Hmmmmm</span><hr size=1> The &quot;holy trinity&quot; may well be an optimal solution for non-AE fighting, but the supposed &quot;non-optimal&quot; solutions including &quot;less desired&quot; classes (Hybrids, pet classes) are only marginally less efficient <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> if at all</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> at good playing skill levels.  The lower the playing skill (and I mean everything right down to target selection, pulling speeds/splits) the bigger the gaps.  The eq-playerbase mindset is by enlarge trapped in the metastable holy-trinity solution .  If the aims are &quot;targetmonster XXX&quot; rather than simply Exp (where your real criterion is &quot;blue monster kills per unit time in high ZEM zone&quot;), then more constraints do come in.<br>
<br>
Now, it is unforunate but most &quot;EQ Lore&quot; such as this is derived from the opinions/abilities of the &quot;lowest common denominator&quot;, where those &quot;gaps&quot;between the more fluid playstyles demanded by non-trinity groups and the rigid mez/assist setup are chasms, but if you want to play EQ with those people who can only follow formula, be my guest.<br>
<br>
The only class I know of that has really significant problems being useful is a wizard without at least a Velk robe,  as their entire killing ability is 100% linked to the prescence of mana regeneration in the group, plus they have no force-multiplicative powers, just addative/auxilary.  Can they still be useful?  Yes,  but they have a serious efficiency problem there unless you're designing pulls for pillaring etc...<br>
<br>
